Scholars explain the evolution of immigration policy, and analyze current conflicts around issues of immigrant rights; activists engaged in the current movement document the ways in which coalitions have been built among immigrants from different nations, and between immigrant and native born peoples. The essays examine the ways in which questions of immigrant rights engage broader issues of identity, including gender, race, and sexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSocial integrationxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aStates.  aUnited.  aexamination.  aimmigration.  amovement.  aprovocative.  arights.1 aBuff, Rachel Ida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCacho, Lisa Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas Gupta, Monisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancouer, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Abner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuzman Molina, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHondagneu-Sotelo, Pierrette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyunhye Cho, Eunice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel